{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505789"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2483"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2483"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.69,0.02,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97630"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2483"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"4082"},{"type":"tags","id":"4100"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97630"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her cervical screening test (CST) results. She is currently using the Mirena intra-uterine device for contraception with no complications. She has been sexually active with three casual partners over the past two months and used condoms irregularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer last cervical screening test was done five years ago with no abnormal results. Her past medical history includes a chlamydia infection four years ago which was adequately treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA routine cervical screening test was performed a week ago (clinician collected at patient\u0027s request) which shows the following results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOncogenic HPV and genotype:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV 16/18: not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV (non 16/18): \u003Cstrong\u003Edetected\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiquid-based cytology (LBC) result:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPossible low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (LSIL)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndocervical component: identified\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the recommended next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer to a specialist for colposcopy","Repeat HPV test in 12 months","Recall the patient in two years for their next cervical screening test","Recall the patient in five years for their next cervical screening test","Collect a new sample for liquid-based cytology in six weeks"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an asymptomatic patient who has undergone a routine Cervical Screening Test (CST). The routine CST is performed from the age of 25 till 74 in a 5-yearly interval (unless an oncogenic HPV is detected or if symptoms develop) and tests for Human Papilloma Virus (HPV) subtypes. If the specimen is a clinician collected specimen and HPV is detected, reflex liquid based cytology is performed. It can also test for \u003Cem\u003Echlamydia, gonorrhoea\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003Etrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003Emycoplasma genitalium\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV genotyping is performed to detect the main oncogenic HPV subtypes, in particular, HPV subtypes 16 and 18. If detected, reflex liquid-based cytology (LBC) aims to classify and detect any epithelial cell abnormalities. If HPV 16/18 is detected, then an immediate \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to a specialist for colposcopy\u003C/strong\u003E is necessary. Similarly, colposcopy is also required if a high-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (HSIL) is detected on LBC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf other HPV subtypes, not 16/18, are detected or a low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (LSIL) is reported, a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat HPV test in 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E is required. It\u0027s important to note that this follow-up test is only a HPV test, not a co-test (HPV and LBC). If HPV not 16/18 is detected at the 12-month follow-up, then reflex liquid-based cytology (LBC) would again be performed, but only if it was a clinician-collected sample. If the follow-up test was a self-collection and is positive for HPV non 16/18, then a cervical sample will need to be collected. If the follow-up test is negative for HPV, the patient can return to the normal screening program with 5-yearly HPV tests (either through clinician or self-collected specimens).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecalling the patient in two years\u003C/strong\u003E for their next CST is not appropriate when a non-16/18 HPV type has been detected. This interval is not part of the current Australian cervical screening guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecalling the patient in five years\u003C/strong\u003E for their next CST would only be appropriate if the current test was negative for all HPV types. Given the detection of a non-16/18 HPV type, more frequent monitoring is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollecting a new sample for liquid-based cytology in six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is only indicated if there are unsatisfactory results from the original test. In this case, the results are satisfactory, and the appropriate management is based on the detected HPV type and cytology findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that a cervical screening test (CST) is NOT the same as a co-test. A CST in the Australian program is primarily an HPV test, with reflex LBC only performed if HPV is detected. A co-test, on the other hand, involves performing both HPV testing AND cytology regardless of HPV results. Co-testing would be indicated in specific situations such as: follow-up after treatment for high-grade abnormalities, investigation of symptoms like abnormal bleeding despite negative HPV testing, or in the management of women with a previous history of adenocarcinoma in situ (AIS). Co-testing provides additional information in these higher-risk scenarios where both HPV status and cellular changes need to be monitored simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Detection of a HPV subtype, not 16/18, with LSIL on cytology indicates that the CST should be repeated in 12 months.","HPV 16/18 detection requires immediate colposcopy regardless of cytology findings.","The Australian cervical screening program recommends 5-yearly HPV testing for women aged 25-74 years."],"references":["National cervical screening program - Understanding the National Cervical Screening Program Management Pathway. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/2025-02/national-cervical-screening-program-understanding-the-national-cervical-screening-program-management-pathway.pdf","Cancer Council Australia Cervical Cancer Screening Working Party. Clinical pathway: cervical screening pathway. Sydney (AU): Cancer Council Australia; 2016, updated 2020 Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/assets/pdf/routine-cervical-screening-flowchart-6-1","Smith M, Hammond I, Saville M. Lessons from the renewal of the National Cervical Screening Program in Australia. Public Health Res Pract. 2019 Jul 31;29(2):2921914. doi: 10.17061/phrp2921914. PMID: 31384888.","Peirson L, Fitzpatrick-Lewis D, Ciliska D, Warren R. Screening for cervical cancer: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Syst Rev 2013; 2:35."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2483"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80230"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-08T10:24:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-08T20:54:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2483"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97630"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta"